fr.reflexe.viewshell.api.config

Interface IConfigUnit

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<String>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IConfigStore

    public interface IConfigUnit
extends Iterable<String>
    Manages read/write configuration properties, providing convenience methods for strings, integers, booleans, UUIDs, binary data, and sequences of values with the same base name.

    Configuration units can be used directly in for-each constructs, to iterate over property names.

    Thread safety: implementations are required to be safe for concurrent read/write access.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    REFLEXE Technologies
    See Also:
    IConfigService.createConfigUnit(), IConfigService.createConfigUnit(java.util.Properties)

      • getStringSequence

        List<String> getStringSequence(String name)
        Gets a list of string properties, beginning with the specified name, if found.

        The first list element will correspond either to a property for which the specified name is an exact match, or for which the name starts as specified, and ends with either "0" or ".1". The next list element will either correspond to a property for which the name starts with a number greater than the previous suffix in sequence (such as ".2", if the previous property began with ".1"). Gaps in the sequence are allowed.

        Parameters:
        name - property name.
        Returns:
        a list of strings. May be empty, but never null.
        Since:
        1.0

      • getStringSequence

        List<String> getStringSequence(String name,
                               boolean allowGaps,
                               int startIndex)
        Gets a list of String properties, beginning with the specified name, if found.

        The first list element will correspond either to a property for which the specified name is an exact match, or for which the name starts as specified, and ends with either "0" or ".1". The next list element will either correspond to a property for which the name starts with a number greater than the previous suffix in sequence (such as ".2", if the previous property began with ".1"). By using the startIndex argument, you can restrict this behaviour. Gaps in the sequence are optionally allowed.

        Parameters:
        name - property name.
        allowGaps - if true, the returned sequence may contain gaps, if false, the returned sequence will only contain values up to the first gap.
        startIndex - must be greater than or equal to zero (if required), or UNSPECIFIED_SEQUENCE_START if the starting index is irrelevant. If required, and if gaps are allowed, then any suffix number greater than or equal to the value of startIndex will be returned. If required, and if gaps are not allowed, then the exact match must for startIndex must exist and only matching properties with consecutive suffix numbers will be returned.
        Returns:
        a list of strings. May be empty, but never null.
        Since:
        1.0

      • getPropertyNameSequence

        List<String> getPropertyNameSequence(String baseName,
                                     boolean allowGaps)
        Gets an ordered list of property names, beginning with the specified base name followed by numeric suffixes (1, 2, 3, etc).

        Consider a set of properties such as:

        remote.host=paris.reflexe.fr
        remote.host.1=rouen.reflexe.fr
        remote.host.2=lyon.reflexe.fr
        remote.host.3=bordeaux.reflexe.fr

        If baseName is remote.host, then this method will return the names of all the above properties, in ascending numerical order.

        Parameters:
        baseName - the property prefix, which in the above examples would be the string remote.host.
        allowGaps - if true, the returned sequence may contain gaps, if false, the returned sequence will only contain names up to the first gap (if any... if there are no gaps, the full sequence will of course be returned).
        Returns:
        all matching names as a list of strings.
        Since:
        1.0

      • toProperties

        Properties toProperties(String prefix)
        Gets a copy of a subset of internal configuration properties.
        Parameters:
        prefix - specifies which internal properties are to be returned. For example, a prefix such as "foo." would return properties such as "foo.bar" and "foo.xyz", but not "bar.xyz" or "bar.foo".
        Returns:
        a copy of this configuration object's internal properties that match the specified prefix.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the prefix ends with "_" or ".".
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        toProperties(String, boolean)

      • toProperties

        Properties toProperties(String prefix,
                        boolean removePrefix)
        Gets a copy of a subset of internal configuration properties, optionally removing the property selection prefix.
        Parameters:
        prefix - specifies which internal properties are to be returned. Given the list of properties "foo", "foo.abc", "foo.xyz", "foobar", and "bar.foo", then using a prefix of "foo" would yield all of these properties except "bar.foo". If null or empty, the prefix is ignored.
        removePrefix - when true, specifies that the prefix should be removed, otherwise false, to retain it. If the character separating the prefix and the rest of the property name is either "." or "_", then that character will be removed if the prefix is removed.
        Returns:
        a copy of this configuration object's internal properties that match the specified prefix.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the prefix ends with "_" or ".".
        Since:
        1.0

        void removeSequence(String name)
             throws ConfigException

        name - the base name of the property to modify. Will only match property names that are followed by a (".") and an integer. As such, it will not affect any other property that begins with an identical name followed by any other character sequence.
        startIndex - the value of the first integer to append, such as 0 or 1.
        values - the new values.
        Throws:
        ConfigException - if the requested change cannot be stored.
        Since:
        1.0
        See Also:
        replaceUuidSequence(String, int, Iterable)
